  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/Tengu/tengu-cockpit/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-gemini-3.1/docs/wiki/Double-Agent-TDD.md', content="# Double-Agent TDD Flow\n\nD.U.H. natively supports Test-Driven Development (TDD) using a multi-agent structure mimicking the classic Driver/Navigator pair-programming dynamic. In this workflow, two LLM personas alternate control over the problem space, stepping through the classic Red-Green-Refactor loop.\n\n## Overview\n\nThe flow is triggered directly from the REPL via the `/tdd` command. Under the hood, the system uses two separate specialized agents.\n\n1. **The Navigator** (reviewer persona): Focuses on constraints, requirements, and clean architectural design.\n2. **The Driver** (coder persona): Focuses exclusively on writing passing code and correctly implemented tests.\n\n## The Six-Phase Contract\n\nOnce initiated, the flow progresses through six strict phases, and the system orchestrates the transitions:\n\n1. **Navigator drafts the test spec.**\n   The Navigator is handed the user's initial prompt and requested to write out what the test suite _should_ look like, boundary conditions to consider, etc.\n\n2. **Driver writes the failing test (RED).**\n   The Driver reads the spec, implements the test using standard tools, and executes it. The execution *must fail* (AssertionError, etc.). If it inadvertently passes, the orchestrator detects this and instructs the Driver to write a tighter test or revise the boundary.\n\n3. **Driver makes it pass (GREEN).**\n   With a successfully failing test, the Driver writes the minimum viable production code to flip the test output to green. The test is rerun and verified.\n\n4. **Navigator proposes a refactor.**\n   The Navigator steps back in, reads the implementation and the tests, and proposes a refactoring plan to improve code quality, maintainability, or readability—while ensuring behavior stays the same.\n\n5. **Driver applies the refactor.**\n   The Driver executes the refactor as directed by the Navigator.\n\n6. **Navigator validates.**\n   A final check by the Navigator ensures the refactor was applied accurately and the tests still pass cleanly.\n\n## Usage\n\nStart the REPL (`duh`) and simply type:\n\n```text\n> /tdd add division to the calculator.py script, handling zero-division with a custom exception\n```\n\nThe REPL will trace the progress:\n\n```\nStarting TDD flow for: add division to the calculator.py script, handling zero-division with a custom exception\n\nPhase 1: Navigator drafting test spec...\nPhase 1 Complete. Spec drafted.\n\nPhase 2: Driver writing failing test (RED)...\nPhase 2 Complete. Failing test written.\n\nPhase 3: Driver writing code to pass test (GREEN)...\nPhase 3 Complete. Test passes.\n\nPhase 4: Navigator proposing refactor...\nPhase 4 Complete. Refactor proposed.\n\nPhase 5: Driver applying refactor...\nPhase 5 Complete. Refactor applied.\n\nPhase 6: Navigator validating refactor...\nPhase 6 Complete. TDD Flow finished.\n```\n\n## Why two agents?\n\nSeparating concerns limits the LLM's tendency to write tautological tests (tests written to pass existing code) or prematurely optimize code while missing edge cases. By forcing the RED stage with an independent agent proposing the spec, the flow stays significantly more rigorous.\n")
